Summary: Structure Types in C#
In C#, a structure (struct) is a value type used to group related variables under one name. It’s similar to a class but has important differences:

Value Type: Stored on the stack (by default), unlike classes which are reference types stored on the heap.

Lightweight: Best for small data models (like coordinates, colors, points).

No Inheritance: Structs cannot inherit from other structs or classes, but they can implement interfaces.

Default Constructor: You cannot define a parameterless constructor; the compiler provides one automatically.

Members Allowed: Fields, properties, methods, constructors (with parameters), indexers, operators, and events.

Initialization: All fields must be assigned before use.

Copy Behavior: When assigned, structs are copied by value, not by reference.

👉 Think of a struct as a compact container for related data, useful when you don’t need the overhead of a class.

🎯 25 Practice Questions with Answers
Basics
Q: What is a struct in C#?
A: A value type that groups related variables under one name, similar to a lightweight class.

Q: Where are structs stored in memory?
A: On the stack (by default), since they are value types.

Q: Can structs inherit from other structs?
A: No, structs cannot inherit from classes or other structs.

Q: Can structs implement interfaces?
A: Yes, structs can implement interfaces.

Q: What is the default accessibility of struct members?
A: Private.

Constructors & Initialization
Q: Can you define a parameterless constructor in a struct?
A: No, the compiler provides one automatically.

Q: Can structs have parameterized constructors?
A: Yes, but all fields must be initialized inside them.

Q: What happens if you don’t initialize struct fields?
A: The compiler forces you to assign values before use.

Q: Can structs have destructors?
A: No, destructors are not allowed in structs.

Q: Can structs have static constructors?
A: Yes, static constructors are allowed.

Behavior & Usage
Q: What happens when you assign one struct to another?
A: A copy of the value is made (value semantics).

Q: Can structs be null?
A: No, unless declared as nullable (e.g., Point?).

Q: Are structs sealed?
A: Yes, implicitly—they cannot be inherited.

Q: Can structs contain methods?
A: Yes, including instance and static methods.

Q: Can structs contain properties?
A: Yes, both auto‑implemented and custom properties.

Advanced
Q: Can structs overload operators?
A: Yes, operator overloading is supported.

Q: Can structs have indexers?
A: Yes, indexers are allowed.

Q: Can structs contain events?
A: Yes, events are supported.

Q: Can structs contain constants and static fields?
A: Yes, both are allowed.

Q: Can structs be generic?
A: Yes, you can define generic structs.

Comparison with Classes
Q: What is the key difference between struct and class assignment?
A: Structs are copied by value; classes are copied by reference.

Q: Which is better for small data models: struct or class?
A: Struct, because it’s lightweight and avoids heap allocation.

Q: Can structs participate in inheritance hierarchies?
A: No, only classes can.

Q: Do structs support polymorphism?
A: Only via interface implementation, not inheritance.

Q: Why might you choose a struct over a class?
A: For performance reasons when modeling small, immutable data.
